Australian cricket captain and his deputy have resigned from their positions for the remainder of the test series following a glaring ball tampering during the third-day match against South Africa in Cape Town on Saturday. Steve Smith and David Warner resigned announced their resignation today prior to the fourth day of the highly entertaining test match, however, they will still take part in today match. Tim Paine has been appointed to lead Australia for the remainder of the 5 test series which the country leads 1 nil. Smith admitted during a news conference after the match that there had been an agreement between a group of senior players during the lunch break about breaking one of the laws of cricket. “I’m not proud of what happened. It’s not within the spirit of the game and my integrity, the team’s integrity, the leadership group’s integrity has come into question and rightfully so. “It’s not on and it won’t happen again, I can promise you that, under my leadership,” Smith said. Cricket Australia CEO James Sutherland said Cricket Australia and the country’s cricket fans expect certain standards of conduct from cricketers who are representing the country and on this occasion, the standards have not been met. “This Test match needs to proceed, and in the interim, we will continue to investigate this matter with the urgency that it demands.” “The Board fully supports the process for an immediate investigation into what occurred in Cape Town. Cricket Australia Chairperson David Peever said they are treating the incident with the seriousness it deserves and they will ensure they have all the required information before announcing the action to be taken. “We regard this as a matter of the utmost seriousness and urgency. We will ensure we have all information available to make the right decisions for Australian Cricket,” Peever said. -TNA Reporter